posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: I think we understand how to incorporate AdvantageKits suggested IO framework with our custom Subsystems. It isnt clear how we would do it for the CTRE Swerve example. Is it even reasonable to do?

Since akit ios are meant for hardware objects, just move all your hardware references (motors, encoders, gyros) into an io file as you would normally. I believe we have a SwerveModuleIO class and a GyroIO class. We instantiate one swerve drive io per module and one gyro io for the whole drive.

That is what I thought. Good to know we understand how this works!

We are now looking at using the CTRE SignalLogger instead of the AdvantageKit logger. That seems to work pretty good.

posts.name: Chadfrom7226
posts.cooked: AdvantageScope will also open CTRE logs natively as well

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: Yup, that is working well for us. The only problem we are having is that we dont see a way to log an array of pose2d. We want to log the information from PathPlanner.

posts.name: Chadfrom7226
posts.cooked: We are logging the Pose2d I believe. Did you see ours?

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked:
Yup, but you are using the AdvantageKit logger. Because we cant easily adapt the CTRE swerve logic to AdvantageKit, we switched to just using the SignalLogger from CTRE . Which is working good (just kinda sucks to pull and transform the data) It also has a bunch of extra data we probably dont need.

I think we are all sorted at this point. We can store a pose as a double and that works for AdvantageScope.

posts.name: Benjamin Hall
posts.cooked: For reference, we log the SwerveDrivetrains Pose2d in our SwerveWithPathPlanner example . AdvantageScope just expects a double array of {x, y, rad} for Pose2d.
